rounds.response:
Got to be careful now—if I don’t block the bottom row, Player 1’s 6-7 will turn into 6-7-(8)=6-7-X, but 8 is already mine.  
Check for threats:  
- Row 2 is blocked (8=O)  
- No immediate diagonal threat (top-left to bottom-right already broken by 4=O; top-right to bottom-left would need 2→4→6 and cell 4 already O).

So I don’t need a block.  
Instead, with cells 5 I could set up a double threat that Player 1 can’t stop:  
 • Horizontal: 3–4–5 (O-O-5) — one move from winning.  

Player 1 has no winning move next turn, so I’ll take the sure win.

[5]
